06623nam a22009735i 9781501730764DE-B159720190920094934.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190920s2018    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017307647 a10.7591/97815017307642doi  a(DE-B1597)503279  a(OCoLC)1030444126  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHQ799.8.J3bC45 2018 7aHIS0210002bisacsh04a305.253/0917342231 aChatani, Sayaka, eauthor.10aNation-Empire :bIdeology and Rural Youth Mobilization in Japan and Its Colonies /cSayaka Chatani. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource :b10 b&w halftones, 3 b&w line drawings, 4 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies of the Weatherhead East Asian Institute, Columbia University00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Transliteration and Translation -- tIntroduction: Nation-Empire as Global and Local History -- tPart 1: THE SO-CALLED INNER TERRITORIES -- t1. National Trends -- t2. From Mobilization to the Social Mobility Complex -- t3. Totalitarian Japanization -- tPart 2: THE SO-CALLED OUTER TERRITORIES -- t4. Colonial Intellectuals -- t5. Finding Rural Youth in Taiwan -- t6. The Emotional Basis for Japanization -- t7. Model Rural Youth in Korean Villages -- t8. Opportunities and Loopholes -- tPart 3: CONSEQUENCES -- t9. As Young Pillars of the Nation-Empire -- tNotes -- tON THE ARCHIVES AND SOURCES -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBy the end of World War II, hundreds of thousands of young men in the Japanese colonies, in particular Taiwan and Korea, had expressed their loyalty to the empire by volunteering to join the army. Why and how did so many colonial youth become passionate supporters of Japanese imperial nationalism? And what happened to these youth after the war? Nation-Empire investigates these questions by examining the long-term mobilization of youth in the rural peripheries of Japan, Taiwan, and Korea. Personal stories and village histories vividly show youth's ambitions, emotions, and identities generated in the shifting conditions in each locality. At the same time, Sayaka Chatani unveils an intense ideological mobilization built from diverse contexts-the global rise of youth and agrarian ideals, Japan's strong drive for assimilation and nationalization, and the complex emotions of younger generations in various remote villages.Nation-Empire engages with multiple historical debates. Chatani considers metropole-colony linkages, revealing the core characteristics of the Japanese Empire; discusses youth mobilization, juxtaposing the Japanese seinendan (village youth associations) with the Boy Scouts and the Hitlerjugend; and examines society and individual subjectivities under totalitarian rule. Her book highlights the shifting state-society transactions of the twentieth-century world through the lens of the Japanese Empire, inviting readers to contend with a new approach to, and a bold vision of, empire study.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 0aNationalismzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aNationalismzKorea (South)xHistoryy20th century. 0aNationalismzTaiwanxHistoryy20th century. 0aRural youthxPolitical activityzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aRural youthxPolitical activityzKorea (South)xHistoryy20th century. 0aRural youthxPolitical activityzTaiwanxHistoryy20th century. 0aYoung menxPolitical activityzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aYoung menxPolitical activityzKorea (South)xHistoryy20th century. 0aYoung menxPolitical activityzTaiwanxHistoryy20th century. 4aChildhood Studies. 4aHistory. 4aJapanese Empire, youth mobilization, nationalism, World War II, WWII, Second